# PostgreSQL Best Practices

## Database Design
- Use proper normalization (3NF minimum)
- Leverage PostgreSQL-specific features
- Use proper data types (JSONB, Arrays, ENUM)
- Implement proper constraints and validation
- Design for performance and scalability
- Plan for growth and optimization

## Advanced Data Types
- Use JSONB for semi-structured data
- Implement array types appropriately
- Use ENUM for fixed value sets
- Use UUID for distributed IDs
- Use RANGE types for ranges
- Choose appropriate composite types

## Table Structure
- Use BIGSERIAL for primary keys
- Implement proper column data types
- Use generated columns where appropriate
- Set proper default values
- Add audit timestamps (created_at, updated_at)
- Use constraints for data integrity

## Naming Conventions
- Use snake_case for table and column names
- Use plural form for table names
- Prefix boolean columns with is/has/should
- Name foreign keys as parent_table_id format
- Use idx_ prefix for indexes
- Use meaningful names for all objects

## Constraints and Validation
- Use primary key on every table
- Implement foreign key constraints properly
- Use unique constraints for unique data
- Add check constraints for validation
- Use NOT NULL for required fields
- Use domains for reusable types

## Indexing Strategy
- Use B-tree indexes for standard queries
- Use GIN indexes for JSONB and arrays
- Use GiST indexes for geometric data
- Create partial indexes for filtered data
- Use expression indexes for computed columns
- Monitor and maintain index performance

## JSONB Operations
- Store complex data in JSONB
- Index JSONB fields with GIN
- Query JSONB efficiently
- Update JSONB data properly
- Use JSONB aggregation functions
- Optimize JSONB performance

## Window Functions
- Use window functions for analytics
- Implement ranking functions properly
- Use aggregate window functions
- Apply frame specifications correctly
- Optimize window function queries
- Document complex window logic

## Common Table Expressions
- Use CTEs for complex queries
- Implement recursive CTEs for hierarchies
- Use multiple CTEs for clarity
- Optimize CTE performance
- Avoid excessive CTE nesting
- Document CTE purposes

## Full-Text Search
- Set up full-text search indexes
- Use proper text search configuration
- Optimize full-text queries
- Implement ranking properly
- Use tsvector efficiently
- Monitor search performance

## Materialized Views
- Create materialized views for expensive queries
- Refresh views appropriately
- Use concurrent refresh
- Index materialized views
- Monitor view maintenance
- Document refresh schedules

## Query Optimization
- Analyze query execution plans with EXPLAIN ANALYZE
- Optimize slow queries
- Use proper JOIN strategies
- Avoid unnecessary functions in WHERE
- Implement proper subqueries
- Use query statistics

## Transaction Management
- Use transactions for related operations
- Set proper isolation levels
- Implement proper error handling
- Use savepoints appropriately
- Monitor transaction performance
- Handle deadlocks properly

## Database Connections
- Implement connection pooling (PgBouncer)
- Set proper connection limits
- Handle connection failures
- Monitor active connections
- Implement proper timeouts
- Clean up connections properly

## Security
- Use parameterized queries (prevent SQL injection)
- Implement proper user roles and privileges
- Use SSL for connections
- Encrypt sensitive data
- Validate all input data
- Implement row-level security

## Performance Tuning
- Configure shared_buffers properly
- Set work_memory appropriately
- Configure effective_cache_size
- Tune maintenance_work_mem
- Implement parallel query execution
- Monitor system performance

## Backup and Recovery
- Implement automated backups
- Use pg_dump for logical backups
- Test backup restoration regularly
- Document recovery procedures
- Monitor backup success
- Plan disaster recovery

## Monitoring and Logging
- Use pg_stat_statements for query analysis
